# Class Notice Communication Plan

Produces a court-ready plan for disseminating class notice that satisfies Rule 23 and due process.

## Prerequisites

1. Class certification order or proposed certification motion
2. Class definition and any subclasses (verbatim)
3. Claims, defenses, and relief sought
4. Court-ordered deadlines (opt-out, objection, fairness hearing, trial)
5. Available class member data sources and quality assessment
6. Settlement terms affecting notice (if applicable)
7. Proposed claims administrator or notice expert (if any)

## Output Structure / Process

**1. Case Header (Table)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| Case name |  |
| Court and case number |  |
| Judge |  |
| Procedural posture |  |
| Certification order date |  |
| Governing rule(s) | Fed. R. Civ. P. 23(c)(2)(B); due process |
| Key deadlines |  |

**2. Legal Standards (Table)**

| Authority | Requirement |
| --- | --- |
| Fed. R. Civ. P. 23(c)(2)(B) | Best notice practicable; individual notice where feasible |
| Due process (Mullane v. Central Hanover Bank & Trust Co.) | Notice reasonably calculated to apprise interested parties |
| Eisen v. Carlisle & Jacquelin | Individual notice to identifiable class members |
| CAFA (28 U.S.C. § 1715) | Government notice for covered settlements (if applicable) |

**3. Class Definition and Identification (Table)**

| Item | Details |
| --- | --- |
| Class definition (verbatim) |  |
| Subclasses (verbatim) |  |
| Estimated class size |  |
| Geographic/temporal limits |  |
| Data sources to identify class |  |
| Data gaps and remediation plan |  |

**4. Required Notice Content (Rule 23(c)(2)(B))**

Checklist:
- Nature of the action
- Definition of the class
- Class claims, issues, and defenses
- Right to enter an appearance through counsel
- Right to request exclusion and method for doing so
- Time and manner for requesting exclusion
- Binding effect of a class judgment on class members

**5. Notice Form Specifications (Table)**

| Element | Requirement |
| --- | --- |
| Tone | Neutral, non-advocacy |
| Readability | Plain language; target ~8th grade when consumer class |
| Languages | Include translations where material class segments are non-English |
| Accessibility | ADA-compliant format; mobile-responsive web |

**6. Delivery Methods and Media Mix (Table)**

| Channel | When Used | Execution Notes |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Direct mail | Identifiable addresses | First-class mail; NCOA updates; re-mailing protocol |
| Email | Reliable email addresses | SPF/DKIM compliance; bounce tracking |
| Publication | Non-identifiable members or supplement | Targeted print/digital; market-specific placements |
| Digital ads | Broad or niche reach | Geo/demo targeting aligned with class |
| Settlement website | Central repository | Hosts notice, claim form, FAQs, key dates |
| Toll-free line | Support | Live + automated; multilingual if needed |

**7. Data Hygiene and Skip-Tracing (Checklist)**

- Run NCOA updates prior to initial mailing
- Track returns and perform skip-tracing on undeliverables
- Re-mail within defined window after address correction
- Maintain audit trail of all address updates

**8. Timeline (Table)**

| Milestone | Date / Offset |
| --- | --- |
| Court approval of plan and notice form |  |
| Data extraction complete |  |
| Website and hotline live |  |
| Initial mail/email launch |  |
| Publication run window |  |
| Opt-out deadline |  |
| Objection deadline |  |
| Fairness hearing / trial |  |
| Due diligence declaration filed |  |

Timing guidance (if not ordered):
- Initial direct notice at least 60–90 days before opt-out deadline
- Publication run for 2–4 weeks aligned with direct notice
- Re-mailing window within 14–21 days after return processing

**9. Budget (Table)**

| Category | Basis | Estimate |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Claims administrator fees | Scope and class size |  |
| Data processing | Records volume |  |
| Printing and mail | Class size; pages; postage |  |
| Publication | Rate cards by outlet |  |
| Website and hosting | Build + maintenance |  |
| Hotline | Call volume estimate |  |
| Translation | Languages and word count |  |
| Contingency | 10–20% reserve |  |

**10. Court Approval Package (Checklist)**

- Proposed notice plan
- Proposed notice forms
- Declaration from notice expert or claims administrator
- Compliance statement for Rule 23 and due process
- CAFA notice plan (if applicable)

**11. Monitoring and Reporting (Table)**

| Metric | Source | Reporting Use |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Mail sent/returned/re-mailed | Mail logs | Due diligence declaration |
| Email delivered/bounced | ESP reports | Effectiveness metrics |
| Publication insertions | Media affidavits | Compliance proof |
| Website traffic | Analytics | Reach assessment |
| Hotline volume | Call logs | FAQ and issue tracking |
| Opt-outs/objections | Administrator tracking | Court reporting |

**12. Exhibits (List)**

- Exhibit A: Proposed long-form notice
- Exhibit B: Postcard or short-form notice
- Exhibit C: Publication notice
- Exhibit D: Media plan and rate cards
- Exhibit E: Declaration of due diligence template

## Guidelines

- Do not disseminate notice before court approval.
- Use verbatim class definitions from the certification order.
- Align deadlines with court orders; avoid invented dates.
- Treat CAFA notice as mandatory when a covered settlement is involved.
- Avoid legalese; clarity and neutrality are mandatory.
- Flag jurisdiction-specific deviations if not in federal court.
- Add `[VERIFY]` to any uncertain citation or rule.
